  • Slice onions thinly. Sliced onions, as opposed to ground or puréed onions, add texture to the curry.
  • Cut potatoes into 5-cm chunks.
  • Make a paste of ginger and garlic using a mortar and pestle. Separately, make a paste of green chillies too.
  • Heat mustard oil in a kadhai. Let it smoke gently and turn pale yellow. Temper with dried red chillies, bay leaves, cardamom, cinnamon, and cloves.
  • Add sliced onions, along with sugar to help caramelise the onions. Fry on medium heat for around 15 minutes.
  • Tilt the kadhai slightly, to allow the oil to pool on one side. Add Kashmiri red chilli powder, turmeric powder, and red chilli powder directly to this oil. Fry for 20 seconds. This will help the curry acquire a rich colour.
  • Add ginger and garlic paste. Fry on medium heat for 3 minutes.
  • Lower the heat and add beaten yoghurt. Cook on low heat for another 3 minutes.
  • Add the green chilli paste, coriander powder, and salt. Keep frying until oil separates.
  • Once oil separates and the onions are a rich brown colour, add the mutton pieces. Sauté on medium heat for 15 minutes.
  • At this point you have two options: (a) You can either continue cooking in the same kadhai for a thicker, more full-bodied curry, or (b) transfer everything to a pressure cooker to speed up the process (this will still produce an extremely tasty, tender and hearty curry).
  • For the kadhai, add 1.8 to 2 L water, cover, and let it simmer until the meat is cooked. Stir every 15 minutes. It should take about 2 hours, depending on the mutton.
  • Add potatoes to the curry, when around 30 to 40 minutes remain. When both the meat and potatoes are done, finish with a pinch of garam masala.
  • To pressure cook, transfer everything to a pressure cooker along with potatoes. Add 500 g water and pressure cook on low heat for 30 minutes or until done.
  • If your curry is too thin, remove the pressure cooker lid and cook off the extra liquid on high heat. Finish with a pinch of garam masala.

  • ‍3 g coriander powder

  • 10 g sugar‍

  • 2 L water (if cooking in the kadhai); 500 g (if using a pressure cooker)
